SoVI's reliance on PCA and its additive nature may muddy the influence of certain input variables. Consider a scenario where a census 
tract has a high poverty rate and also a high median housing value. If poverty rate and median housing value have similar, yet inverted 
loadings in their respective factors, say, 0.8 for poverty and -0.8 for median house value, when the SoVI score is calculated for that 
tract they will effectively cancel each other out (0.8 + -0.8 = 0). 

K-means does not suffer from this problem, since the influence of every variable is effictively accounted for during the clustering
process. Both the high poverty rate and high median housing value affect the cluster assignment of our hypothetical tract. Thus, the 
tract could be more accurately identified as, for example, being in a transition zone between economic tiers or being in a historically 
segregated area,rather than just being assigned "medium" or "low" vulnerability. Further, FCM analysis could clarify whether the tract 
belongs to  a unique cluster of similar tracts, or if it is being pulled equally towards low vulnerability and high vulnerability clusters. 

Both methods accomplish the goal of reducing a large set of variables into a smaller set of interpretable groups. But K-means may be 
more "honest" than SoVI scores because it allows for more complex interpretations of the interactions between input variables. Nothing 
is "cancelled out" by the factor loadings in clustering assignment, even when clusters are created based on PCA components and not the
raw variables themselves. 
